Purpose
-------
Self-contained copy of secp256k1_ecmult_multi_var (the
Pippenger/Straus multi-scalar multiplication used by libsecp256k1
for Schnorr batch verification) plus its supporting machinery:
scalar/field/group arithmetic, scratch-space allocator, and
generator precomputation tables.

Why self-contained
------------------
The vendored MSM never passes its internal types
(secp256k1_gej, secp256k1_scalar, etc.) across the public-API
boundary. By vendoring those types alongside the MSM, the
vendored module's correctness is independent of the version of
libsecp256k1 that the rest of mpt-crypto links against. This
PR therefore does not require any change to the existing
libsecp256k1 dep pin (currently secp256k1/0.7.1 via Conan).

Symbol naming
-------------
All vendored symbols are renamed from the secp256k1_* namespace
to mpt_secp256k1_* to avoid linker collisions with the linked
libsecp256k1 binary that mpt-crypto continues to use for the
public-API surface (tweak_mul, pubkey_combine, ecdh, etc.).

Drift detection
---------------
None. We follow the same operational model as the Conan lockfile
under `conan/lockfile/`: pin known-good state, re-sync deliberately
when there is a reason (a published security fix, a performance
improvement we want to pull in, etc.). No automated tripwire.

Sync procedure
--------------
To re-sync against upstream:

  1. Note the new upstream commit hash and tag
  2. Re-export the file list below from upstream at the new tag
  3. Re-apply the symbol renames (see rename_symbols.sh, if used)
  4. Run the calibration test in tests/test_mpt_msm.c
  5. Update this file: Commit, Tag, Vendored on
  6. Open a PR with the diff for review

Local edits
-----------
- util.h: changed `#include "../include/secp256k1.h"` to
  `#include <secp256k1.h>` so the include resolves through the
  linked libsecp256k1 install rather than upstream's src-relative
  layout. Public secp256k1.h surface is stable; no private-type
  coupling.

Compile-time symbol rename
--------------------------
The CMake build applies two compile-time renames to avoid
linker collisions with the linked libsecp256k1 binary, which
exports the same generator-table data symbols:

  -Dsecp256k1_pre_g=mpt_secp256k1_pre_g
  -Dsecp256k1_pre_g_128=mpt_secp256k1_pre_g_128

These are the only renames. All other upstream identifiers
remain unchanged because the vendored sources are included
into a single wrapper translation unit (mpt_msm.c) and the
upstream functions are file-static — they cannot collide
across translation units. See third_party/secp256k1-msm/README.md
for the full rationale.

